#chosen model showing binomial logistic regression model
glm_binom_model <- glm(chicks_fledged / eggs_hatched ~ treatment, 
                       data = tit_data, family = quasibinomial, weights = eggs_hatched)
summary(glm_binom_model)

check_model(glm_binom_model)

#anova show dispersion â 1 for both tests. 
#P > 5%, meaning the treatment vs control do not show significant diff. 
#unsure how to trust "check_model" since it has been known to have bugs after update. 
#code takes the results of a logistic regression model, 
#extracts predicted probabilities and standard errors for those
#predictions, and then calculates the fitted values along with upper and lower
#bounds for logistic regression model predictions. 

tit_data_augmented <- augment(glm_binom_model, type.predict = "response", se_fit = TRUE) |> 
  mutate(
    fitted = plogis(.fitted), 
    lower = plogis(.fitted + .se.fit * 1.96),
    upper = plogis(.fitted - .se.fit * 1.96)
  )
  1. Make a publication-quality plot showing the raw data and the fitted model with confidence intervals.
plot <- ggplot(tit_data, aes(x = treatment, y = chicks_fledged / eggs_hatched, fill = treatment)) +
  geom_violin(alpha = 0.5) +
  stat_summary(fun = mean, geom = "point", shape = 21, size = 3) +
  stat_summary(fun.data = mean_cl_boot, geom = "errorbar", width = 0.1) +   #mean_cl_boot requires Hmisc - package. 
  geom_point(data = tit_data,
             aes(y = chicks_fledged / eggs_hatched,
                 color = treatment, shape = treatment),
             position = position_jitterdodge(jitter.width = 0.5, dodge.width = 0.8)) +
  labs(x = "Treatment", y = "Proportion of Chicks Fledged",
       title = "Violin Plot with Confidence Intervals") +
  theme_minimal()

print(plot)

Figure 1: Plot for publication with raw data as dots/triangles. Errorbars included in the same color as treatments.

The model results indicate that there is not a significant effect of the treatment on the number of chicks fledged per eggs hatched. The intercept coefficient is estimated to be 2.2490 with a standard error of 0.4406, and it is statistically significant (t = 5.104, p < 0.001). The treatment coefficient for the âHeatedâ treatment is estimated to be -0.6288 with a standard error of 0.5700, but it is not statistically significant (t = -1.103, p = 0.274). The null deviance is 208.21 on 65 degrees of freedom, and the residual deviance is 203.15 on 64 degrees of freedom. The analysis of deviance table shows that the addition of the treatment term to the model does not significantly improve the model fit based on the chi-square test (p = 0.2635) or the F-test (p = 0.2677). These results suggest that the treatment does not have a significant impact on the number of chicks fledged per eggs hatched.

2)  Loading/reading data from source and selecting relevant columns in csv-file.

"treatment" - Control or Heated "eggs_hatched" - number of eggs that hatched "chicks_fledged" - number of chicks that fledged

```{r}
#| label: importing data
# Read the CSV file into a DataFrame
tit_data <- read_csv("ACC_demographicData.csv") |>
  janitor::clean_names() |> # Clean column names using the janitor package
  select(treatment, eggs_hatched, chicks_fledged) # Select specific columns
  

```

```{r}
glm_binom_model <- glm(chicks_fledged / eggs_hatched ~ treatment,

```

```{r}
#| label: checking chosen model

summary(glm_binom_model)

anova(glm_binom_model, test = "Chi") 
anova(glm_binom_model, test = "F")
check_model(glm_binom_model)

#anova show dispersion â 1 for both tests. 
#P > 5%, meaning the treatment vs control do not show significant diff. 
#unsure how to trust "check_model" since it has been known to have bugs after update. 

```

```{r}
#| label: augmenting data
#code takes the results of a logistic regression model, 
#extracts predicted probabilities and standard errors for those
#predictions, and then calculates the fitted values along with upper and lower
#bounds for logistic regression model predictions. 

tit_data_augmented <- augment(glm_binom_model, type.predict = "response", se_fit = TRUE) |> 
  mutate(
    fitted = plogis(.fitted), 
    lower = plogis(.fitted + .se.fit * 1.96),
    upper = plogis(.fitted - .se.fit * 1.96)
  )
```

3.  Make a publication-quality plot showing the raw data and the fitted model with confidence intervals.

```{r}
#| label: creating plot

plot <- ggplot(tit_data, aes(x = treatment, y = chicks_fledged / eggs_hatched, fill = treatment)) +
  geom_violin(alpha = 0.5) +
  stat_summary(fun = mean, geom = "point", shape = 21, size = 3) +
  stat_summary(fun.data = mean_cl_boot, geom = "errorbar", width = 0.1) +   #mean_cl_boot requires Hmisc - package. 
  geom_point(data = tit_data,
             aes(y = chicks_fledged / eggs_hatched,
                 color = treatment, shape = treatment),
             position = position_jitterdodge(jitter.width = 0.5, dodge.width = 0.8)) +
  labs(x = "Treatment", y = "Proportion of Chicks Fledged",
       title = "Violin Plot with Confidence Intervals") +
  theme_minimal()

print(plot)

```

Figure 1: Plot for publication with raw data as dots/triangles. Errorbars included in the same color as treatments.

The model results indicate that there is not a significant effect of the treatment on the number of chicks fledged per eggs hatched. The intercept coefficient is estimated to be 2.2490 with a standard error of 0.4406, and it is statistically significant (t = 5.104, p \< 0.001). The treatment coefficient for the "Heated" treatment is estimated to be -0.6288 with a standard error of 0.5700, but it is not statistically significant (t = -1.103, p = 0.274). The null deviance is 208.21 on 65 degrees of freedom, and the residual deviance is 203.15 on 64 degrees of freedom. The analysis of deviance table shows that the addition of the treatment term to the model does not significantly improve the model fit based on the chi-square test (p = 0.2635) or the F-test (p = 0.2677). **These results suggest that the treatment does not have a significant impact on the number of chicks fledged per eggs hatched.**
